SIMPLE: notwithstanding
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Notwithstanding
<hw>Not`with*stand"ing</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prep.</pos> <def>Without
prevention, or obstruction from or by; in spite of.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We gentil women bee⟦br⟧
Loth to displease any wight,⟦br⟧
<qex>Notwithstanding</qex> our great right.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer's
Dream.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Those on whom Christ bestowed miraculous cures were so transported
that their gratitude made them, <qex>notwithstanding</qex> his
prohibition, proclaim the wonders he had done.</q> <rj><qau>Dr. H.
More.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Notwithstanding</xex> was, by Johnson and Webster,
viewed as a participle absolute, an English equivalent of the Latin
<xex>non obstante</xex>. Its several meanings, either as preposition,
adverb, or conjunction, are capable of being explained in this view.
Later grammarians, while admitting that the word was originally a
participle, and can be treated as such, prefer to class it as a
preposition or disjunctive conjunction.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- In spite of; despite.</syn> <usage> --
<er>Notwithstanding</er>, <er>In spite of</er>, <er>Despite</er>. Of
these, only <ex>notwithstanding</ex> can be used postpositively; <as>as,
I will go, the weather <ex>notwithstanding</ex></as>. With respect to
meaning, these words and phrases are often interchanged, but there is a
difference between them, chiefly in strength. <xex>Notwithstanding</xex>
is the weaker term, and simply points to some obstacle that may exist;
as, I shall go, <xex>notwithstanding</xex> the rain. <xex>In spite</xex>
or <xex>despite of</xex> has reference primarily to active opposition to
be encountered from others; as, ⟦ldquo⟧I'll be, in man's
<xex>despite</xex>, a monarch; ⟦rdquo⟧ ⟦ldquo⟧I'll keep mine own,
<xex>despite of</xex> all the world.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Shak.</au> Hence, these
words, when applied to <xex>things</xex>, suppose greater opposition
than <xex>notwithstanding</xex>. We should say. ⟦rdquo⟧He was thrust
rudely out of doors <xex>in spite of</xex> his entreaties,⟦rdquo⟧ rather
than ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>notwithstanding</xex>⟦rdquo⟧. On the other hand, it
would be more civil to say, ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Notwithstanding</xex> all you
have said, I must still differ with you.⟦rdquo⟧</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Notwithstanding</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Notwithstanding
<hw>Not`with*stand"ing</hw>, <pos>adv. ⟦or⟧ conj.</pos> <ety>[Originally
the participle of <ets>withstand</ets>, with <ets>not</ets>
prefixed.]</ety> <def>Nevertheless; however; although; <as>as, I shall
go, <ex>notwithstanding</ex> it rains</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I will surely rend the kingdom from thee, and will give it to thy
servant. <qex>Notwithstanding</qex>, in thy days I will not do it.</q>
<rj><qau>1 Kings xi. 11, 12.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They which honor the law as an image of the wisdom of God himself,
are, <qex>notwithstanding</qex>, to know that the same had an end in
Christ.</q> <rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You did wisely and honestly too, <qex>notwithstanding</qex>⟦br⟧
She is the greatest beauty in the parish.</q>
<rj><qau>Fielding.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Notwithstanding that</b></col>, <cd>notwithstanding;
although.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These days were ages to him, <qex>notwithstanding that</qex> he
was basking in the smiles of the pretty Mary.</q> <rj><qau>W.
Irving.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Nouch</ent>⟦br⟧
